# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1914-boston-braves-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] The 1871 season was the first season of the Boston Red Stockings franchise, now known as the Atlanta Braves.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] They were formed in 1871 by Boston businessman and Ashburnham native Ivers Whitney Adams.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] The team was composed of former players of the defunct Cincinnati Red Stockings franchise, who were brought to Boston and kept the name with them.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] Led and managed by baseball pioneer Harry Wright, the new Boston team would join the newly formed National Association of Professional Base Ball Players for the 1871 season and finish the year in third place with a record of 20–10.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started all 31 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 19 wins.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] Catcher Cal McVey finished second in the league batting race with a .431 average.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1871-boston-red-stockings-season] From this team, Harry Wright, Al Spalding, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1871-major-league-baseball-season] The tenth founding member, the National club of Washington, did not enter a team for the championship until 1872.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] The **1872 Boston Red Stockings season** was the second season of the franchise.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] They won the National Association championship.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] Managed by Harry Wright, Boston finished with a record of 39–8 to win the pennant by 7.5 games.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started all 48 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 38 wins.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] Second baseman Ross Barnes won the league batting title with a .430 batting average.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1872-boston-red-stockings-season] Harry Wright, Al Spalding, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] The **1873 Boston Red Stockings season** was the third season of the franchise.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] They won their second consecutive National Association championship.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] Managed by Harry Wright, Boston finished with a record of 43–16 to win the pennant by 4 games.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started 54 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 41 wins.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] Second baseman Ross Barnes won the league batting title with a .431 batting average, and catcher Deacon White topped the circuit with 77 runs batted in.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1873-boston-red-stockings-season] Harry Wright, Al Spalding, first baseman Jim O'Rourke, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] The **1874 Boston Red Stockings season** was the fourth season of the franchise.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] They won their third consecutive National Association championship.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Managed by Harry Wright, Boston finished with a record of 52–18 to win the pennant by 7.5 games.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started 69 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 52 wins.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Outfielder Cal McVey led the league with 71 runs batted in, and he paced the Boston offense which scored more runs than any other team.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Harry Wright, Al Spalding, first baseman Jim O'Rourke, catcher Deacon White, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] The **1875 Boston Red Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Boston Red Stockings franchise.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] They won their fourth consecutive National Association championship.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] Managed by Harry Wright, Boston finished with a record of 71–8 to win the pennant by 15 games.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started 62 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 54 wins.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] Catcher Deacon White (.367), second baseman Ross Barnes (.364), and first baseman Cal McVey (.355) finished 1–2–3 in the league's batting race.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] McVey paced the circuit with 87 runs batted in, and outfielder Jim O'Rourke had the most home runs, with 6.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] The Boston offense scored more runs than any other team in the NA.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] According to the FiveThirtyEight ELO rating system, they are the greatest team of all time.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] Harry Wright, Al Spalding, Jim O'Rourke, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] This was the last season of the Association, which dissolved at the end of the year.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings club would join the new National League in 1876.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1876-boston-red-caps-season] The **1876 Boston Red Caps season** was the sixth season of the franchise.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1876-boston-red-caps-season] With the dissolution of the National Association, the Boston team joined the brand new National League.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1876-boston-red-caps-season] The team name was changed from the Boston Red Stockings to the **Boston Red Caps** to avoid confusion with the new Cincinnati Red Stockings team.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1876-boston-red-caps-season] Some of the players from the previous year's team defected to other ballclubs, so the team finished further down in the standings this season.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1914-boston-braves-season] The **1914 Boston Braves season** was the 44th season of the franchise.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1914-boston-braves-season] The team finished first in the National League, winning the pennant by 10½ games over the New York Giants after being in last place in the NL at midseason.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1914-boston-braves-season] The team, which became known as the **1914 Miracle Braves**, went on to sweep the Philadelphia Athletics in the World Series.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1914-boston-braves-season] The Braves performed one of the most memorable reversals in major league history, going from last place to first place in two months, becoming the first team to win a pennant after being in last place on the Fourth of July.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1914-boston-braves-season] After finishing in fifth place in 1913 with a record of 69 wins and 82 losses, the Braves were not expected to be contenders.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1914-boston-braves-season] They spent the first part of the season in last place, posting a record of 26 wins and 40 losses in early July.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1914-boston-braves-season] Led by three pitchers, Dick Rudolph, Bill James, and Lefty Tyler, the team began to win games, taking over first place for good on September 8.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1914-boston-braves-season] Their record over their final 87 games was 68–19 for a winning percentage of .782.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1914-boston-braves-season] Infielders Johnny Evers and Rabbit Maranville led the league in double plays.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1914-boston-braves-season] The Braves went on to sweep Connie Mack's heavily favored Athletics in four games in the 1914 World Series.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1914-boston-braves-season] The team became known as the "Miracle" Braves and remain one of the most storied comeback teams in baseball history.
[src:1914-boston-braves-season/1914-boston-braves-season] The franchise would not win another pennant until 1948.
